d and consume, the look and feel is secondary at best. You could layout the content to make it look like a text file with a menu and search, and no one would care if they can easily get what they came for. Boring yes, but it remains functional and fulfills its purpose. Have you ever paid any attention to the design of Google\'s main page and search results? Or have you seldom noticed it? I\'ll agree that the UI in some Google products is not the best, but their main line - search - is excellent even though it looks boring. I\'ll bet that you use it everyday despite this. And you know why? because it functions exceptionally well, my grandma can use it like a pro, and it gives you what you want. It\'s the very reason Google rose to mind blowing success nearly overnight.\r\n\r\nI\'m not trying to piss anybody off, design is hard and important, but becomes counter-productive if your number one concern is not the user. No one wants a site that looks boring, humans appreciate visual appeal. The best work comes when great designers and developers work together at each step of the process and can dish and receive criticism to push each discipline to its limits.\r\n\r\nI\'m not on your website to appreciate art. Don\'t overload my senses please.','Creative','','inherit','closed','closed','','6-revision-v1','','','2017-12-24 07:50:38','2017-12-24 07:50:38','',6,'http://derulski.local/?p=29',0,'revision','',0),(30,1,'2017-12-24 07:53:20','2017-12-24 07:53:20','Grab a dictionary. look up \'creative.\'\r\n\r\n\"relating to or involving the imagination or original ideas, especially in the production of an artistic work.\"\r\n\r\nIf we go by this definition, then nearly all the people involved in the creation of webpages, aside from copywriters, are not creative. Huh? Read the definition again. Think. When was the last time you created something original when designing a web page? As far as I can tell, 98% of the mock-ups I look at are just recycled hybrids of the same shit with different colors, fonts, positions, and images. Re-skining does not exactly qualify as original. But does that really mean it is not creative?\r\n\r\nOk, clearly this definition sucks. Albeit we have become accustomed to many \'standard\' layouts - for good reasons - there is more to it than just moving things around and dropping in some font. Keeping everything in harmony and proportion is an art. Keeping within baselines is discipline. Working within constraints and making it look like you are pushing the boundaries is creative. I argue that the best design is when the user does not notice it. To me, that is the pinnacle of creative in Web design. It is much harder to achieve than bells and whistles. I challenge you to come up with one disadvantage this has for the user.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the thing, next to no one visits your site to check out the design. They want information or are trying to complete some action. If they are not noticing the design, it means it is not getting in their way and conforms to the content. As long as everything is intuitive and the content is easy to find and consume, the look and feel is secondary at best. You could layout the content to make it look like a text file with a menu and search, and no one would care if they can easily get what they came for. Boring yes, but it remains functional and fulfills its purpose. Have you ever paid any attention to the design of Google\'s main page and search results? Or have you seldom noticed it? I\'ll agree that the UI in some Google products is not the best, but their main line - search - is excellent even though it looks boring. I\'ll bet that you use it everyday despite this. And you know why? because it functions exceptionally well, my grandma can use it like a pro, and it gives you what you want. It\'s the very reason Google rose to mind blowing success nearly overnight.\r\n\r\nI\'m not trying to piss anybody off, design is hard and important, but becomes counter-productive if your number one concern is not the user. No one wants a site that looks boring, humans appreciate visual appeal. The best work comes when great designers and developers work together at each step of the process and can dish and receive criticism to push each discipline to its limits.\r\n\r\nI\'m not on your website to appreciate art. Don\'t overload my senses please.','Let\'s talk about Creative','','inherit','closed','closed','','6-revision-v1','','','2017-12-24 07:53:20','2017-12-24 07:53:20','',6,'http://derulski.local/?p=30',0,'revision','',0),(31,1,'2017-12-24 08:03:05','2017-12-24 08:03:05','Grab a dictionary. look up \'creative.\'\r\n\r\n\"relating to or involving the imagination or original ideas, especially in the production of an artistic work.\"\r\n\r\nIf we go by this definition, then nearly all the people involved in the creation of webpages, aside from copywriters, are not creative. Huh? Read the definition again. Think. When was the last time you created something original when designing a web page? As far as I can tell, 98% of the mock-ups I look at are just recycled hybrids of the same shit with different colors, fonts, positions, and images. Re-skinning does not exactly qualify as original. It\'s primarily re-purposing done well by professionals with good taste. But does that really mean it is not creative?\r\n\r\nOk, clearly this definition sucks. Albeit we have become accustomed to many \'standard\' layouts - for good reasons - there is more to it than just moving things around and dropping in some font. Keeping everything in harmony and proportion is an art. Keeping within baselines is discipline. Working within constraints and making it look like you are pushing the boundaries is creative. I argue that the best design is when the user does not notice it. To me, that is the pinnacle of creative in Web design. It is much harder to achieve than bells and whistles. I challenge you to come up with one disadvantage this has for the user.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the thing, next to no one visits your site to check out the design. They want information or are trying to complete some action. If they are not noticing the design, it means it is not getting in their way and conforms to the content. As long as everything is intuitive and the content is easy to find and consume, the look and feel is secondary at best. You could layout the content to make it look like a text file with a menu and search, and no one would care if they can easily get what they came for. Boring yes, but it remains functional and fulfills its purpose. Have you ever paid any attention to the design of Google\'s main page and search results? Or have you seldom noticed it? I\'ll agree that the UI in some Google products is not the best, but their main line - search - is excellent even though it looks boring. I\'ll bet that you use it everyday despite this. And you know why? because it functions exceptionally well, my grandma can use it like a pro, and it gives you what you want. It\'s the very reason Google rose to mind blowing success nearly overnight.\r\n\r\nI\'m not trying to piss anybody off, albeit a reality check could benefit some. Design is hard and important, but becomes counter-productive if your number one concern is not the user. No one wants a site that looks boring, humans appreciate visual appeal. The best work comes when great designers and developers work together at each step of the process and can dish and receive criticism to push each discipline to its limits. If you need a safe zone to shelter from this, you are in the wrong industry.\r\n\r\nI\'m not on your website to appreciate art. Don\'t overload my senses please.','Let\'s talk about Creative','','inherit','closed','closed','','6-revision-v1','','','2017-12-24 08:03:05','2017-12-24 08:03:05','',6,'http://derulski.local/?p=31',0,'revision','',0),(32,1,'2017-12-24 08:04:21','2017-12-24 08:04:21','Grab a dictionary. look up \'creative.\'\r\n\r\n\"relating to or involving the imagination or origin